WEBVTT

1
00:00:14.973 --> 00:00:16.933
- 2701!
Get the fuck out!

2
00:00:16.975 --> 00:00:18.435
- Is there
a MedicAlert bracelet?

3
00:00:18.518 --> 00:00:20.937
- Did you get an ID on him?
- Student ID.

4
00:00:21.021 --> 00:00:22.897
Name says Jackson Davis.
- That's a start.

5
00:00:22.939 --> 00:00:25.316
Jackson. what's going on?
- Title 18!

6
00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:26.943
Title section 508!
- Javadi. you're with us.

7
00:00:26.985 --> 00:00:28.737
- We're gonna take good care
of you. Mr. Davis.

8
00:00:28.778 --> 00:00:30.196
You're in a safe place.
- You're okay.

9
00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:31.364
- Get off!
- Trauma One.

10
00:00:31.448 --> 00:00:32.949
- Reasonableness! 2709!
- Okay. okay. Jackson.

11
00:00:33.033 --> 00:00:33.950
We're gonna need you
to calm down

12
00:00:34.034 --> 00:00:35.702
to get the Taser barbs
out of your neck.

13
00:00:35.785 --> 00:00:37.454
- Do you need to jump on that?
- Mm-mm.

14
00:00:37.495 --> 00:00:39.789
Covering calls for Dana.

15
00:00:39.831 --> 00:00:41.541
- Stop talking to me.

16
00:00:41.624 --> 00:00:43.501
You can't! Title 2710--

17
00:00:43.585 --> 00:00:45.170
- Hard to assess pupils.
- [grunts]

18
00:00:45.253 --> 00:00:46.921
Hard to assess anything.
- Yeah. yeah.

19
00:00:46.963 --> 00:00:48.131
Wait till after he's sedated.

20
00:00:48.214 --> 00:00:49.674
- 10 of olanzapine.
- No. no.

21
00:00:49.758 --> 00:00:51.134
That'll take 15 minutes
to kick in.

22
00:00:51.217 --> 00:00:53.428
Uh. 5 of droperidol
puts him down in 5.

23
00:00:53.470 --> 00:00:55.263
- No. you can't give it
without knowing his QT.

24
00:00:55.305 --> 00:00:57.974
- Two beats of a rhythm strip
before he took off the leads.

25
00:00:58.058 --> 00:00:59.434
- No.

26
00:00:59.476 --> 00:01:00.977
You can't be in here.
Get out!

27
00:01:01.019 --> 00:01:02.645
- That looks good.
Go with the droperidol.

28
00:01:02.729 --> 00:01:04.813
- Get the fuck out!
Get off me!

29
00:01:04.855 --> 00:01:06.649
- Do we take
the Taser barbs out?

30
00:01:06.691 --> 00:01:08.151
- 2701.
- No.

31
00:01:08.193 --> 00:01:09.736
We got to wait
till he calms down first.

32
00:01:09.819 --> 00:01:12.447
- Get off me. man.
2901. get out!

33
00:01:12.489 --> 00:01:14.324
Get out!
2710.

34
00:01:14.407 --> 00:01:16.868
Title 18. section--
1938.

35
00:01:16.951 --> 00:01:20.330
- Mr. Randall.
happy 20th anniversary

36
00:01:20.413 --> 00:01:22.499
and a very happy
Fourth of July.

37
00:01:22.539 --> 00:01:24.334
But no sex fireworks
for you tonight.

38
00:01:24.375 --> 00:01:25.627
Give everything
a chance to heal.

39
00:01:25.668 --> 00:01:27.295
- Don't worry. I will.

40
00:01:27.337 --> 00:01:29.297
Thanks. Doc.
Ow.

41
00:01:29.339 --> 00:01:31.257
- We're going right back
through here. okay. ma'am?

42
00:01:31.341 --> 00:01:32.509
- Oh. thank you.

43
00:01:32.592 --> 00:01:34.134
- Change the dressing
twice a day.

44
00:01:34.176 --> 00:01:37.097
Doggy bag of the ointment
and nonstick gauze.

45
00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:38.598
- Cool.
I know the drill.

46
00:01:38.681 --> 00:01:40.350
Come back if it starts
to ache or stink.

47
00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:42.435
- Exactly.
Good luck. Stay safe.

48
00:01:42.519 --> 00:01:44.104
- Oh. shit. it's Daddy.
with your daddy.

49
00:01:44.187 --> 00:01:46.815
- Lord. what'd
they get up to now?

50
00:01:46.856 --> 00:01:48.358
- Treatin' and streetin'.

51
00:01:48.441 --> 00:01:50.652
- "Pros from Dover."

52
00:01:50.693 --> 00:01:52.070
- I'm sorry. Ms. Graham.

53
00:01:52.152 --> 00:01:54.364
I just saw the ASL note
in your chart.

54
00:01:54.447 --> 00:01:55.990
This is Lindsey.

55
00:01:56.032 --> 00:01:59.410
We'll bring you back
as soon as possible.

56
00:01:59.494 --> 00:02:00.703
Stay with her.

57
00:02:00.745 --> 00:02:02.038
[indistinct chatter]

58
00:02:02.122 --> 00:02:04.707
All right.
Who here needs help?

59
00:02:04.791 --> 00:02:06.793
[indistinct chatter]

60
00:02:06.876 --> 00:02:08.294
You?
You need help?

61
00:02:08.377 --> 00:02:11.047
- Oh. no. no. no. ma'am.
I've been on these since 1987.

62
00:02:11.131 --> 00:02:13.466
This one here.
he got dizzy. fell down.

63
00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:15.718
- Forgot
my blood-pressure medication.

64
00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.555
I left it back home in Georgia.

65
00:02:20.098 --> 00:02:21.558
- And presto.

66
00:02:21.641 --> 00:02:24.352
We're back. Mr. Digby.
with some IV antibiotics.

67
00:02:24.394 --> 00:02:28.022
First we scrub your outsides.
then we clean your insides.

68
00:02:28.064 --> 00:02:29.899
What do you need to document
in his chart?

69
00:02:29.983 --> 00:02:32.067
- Uh. time started.
time completed.

70
00:02:32.152 --> 00:02:33.570
and any adverse reactions.

71
00:02:33.611 --> 00:02:36.197
- What else?

72
00:02:36.239 --> 00:02:39.742
- Um. lot number
on the antibiotic vial.

73
00:02:39.784 --> 00:02:41.494
- Excellent.
Mr. Digby.

74
00:02:41.578 --> 00:02:43.079
- It's just Digby.

75
00:02:43.163 --> 00:02:45.874
- Digby. why'd you wait
so long to come see us?

76
00:02:47.417 --> 00:02:49.752
- I don't like
going to doctors.

77
00:02:49.793 --> 00:02:51.087
- Well. that makes two of us.

78
00:02:51.171 --> 00:02:52.797
We all need help
from time to time.

79
00:02:52.881 --> 00:02:55.633
Think maybe we could arrange
for some ongoing care?

80
00:02:55.716 --> 00:02:58.595
- I just kind of want
to get patched up. you know?

81
00:02:58.636 --> 00:03:00.263
- I do know.

82
00:03:00.346 --> 00:03:03.683
But that's today.
What's tomorrow?

83
00:03:03.766 --> 00:03:05.768
- Sunday.

84
00:03:05.810 --> 00:03:08.688
- Use the system.
That's what it's there for.

85
00:03:08.771 --> 00:03:11.232
Buddy of mine. Dylan.
knows all the angles.

86
00:03:11.274 --> 00:03:13.568
He even works
the occasional miracle.

87
00:03:13.610 --> 00:03:16.112
You think maybe
I could have him stop by?

88
00:03:18.114 --> 00:03:19.616
- I guess. yeah.

89
00:03:19.657 --> 00:03:20.658
- Great.

90
00:03:20.742 --> 00:03:22.785
How about a sandwich?
- Yeah.

91
00:03:22.827 --> 00:03:24.704
Yes. please.

92
00:03:27.248 --> 00:03:28.625
- We always offer.

93
00:03:28.708 --> 00:03:31.419
Two most important things--
that they know we're here

94
00:03:31.461 --> 00:03:33.796
and that we'll never
stop offering.

95
00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.215
- Thanks for covering.
Princess.

96
00:03:35.298 --> 00:03:36.633
- Anytime.

97
00:03:36.716 --> 00:03:38.468
- Yo. can I get
some help over here?

98
00:03:38.551 --> 00:03:40.220
- Yeah.
What's going on. man?

99
00:03:40.303 --> 00:03:41.971
- The crazy kid in there.
screaming.

100
00:03:42.055 --> 00:03:43.973
- All right. have a seat.
- Yeah. that's him.

101
00:03:44.015 --> 00:03:45.600
Still going nuts.

102
00:03:45.642 --> 00:03:47.936
Probably meth--
fucking animal.

103
00:03:47.977 --> 00:03:49.938
- What's your name. sir?
- You don't understand!

104
00:03:49.978 --> 00:03:52.148
- Tony Chinchiolo.
campus security.

105
00:03:52.190 --> 00:03:53.816
Yeah. I was at work
when this happened.

106
00:03:53.858 --> 00:03:55.985
so I'm gonna need
everything documented.

107
00:03:56.027 --> 00:03:57.320
- Okay.

108
00:03:57.362 --> 00:03:59.989
- All right.
Heart rate's 89.

109
00:04:00.031 --> 00:04:01.699
Pulse ox 97.

110
00:04:01.783 --> 00:04:03.201
Scalp lac's tiny--

111
00:04:03.284 --> 00:04:04.202
5 millimeters.
- Ow.

112
00:04:04.285 --> 00:04:05.995
- Should hold together
with Dermabond.

113
00:04:06.037 --> 00:04:07.997
- Kid threw
a fucking chair at me.

114
00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:09.916
- Work-related injury
gets a full exam.

115
00:04:09.999 --> 00:04:12.001
Jesse here will take you.
- Oh. no.

116
00:04:12.085 --> 00:04:13.503
I-I'm gonna stay here
till the cops come

117
00:04:13.586 --> 00:04:16.339
so I can give my statement
and so I can watch him.

118
00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:17.839
- Yeah.

119
00:04:17.882 --> 00:04:20.969
- Trust me. you do not want
him getting out of there.

120
00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.554
Ow. fuck.

121
00:04:23.638 --> 00:04:27.183
- Did she say anything?
- No more than she said to you.

122
00:04:27.267 --> 00:04:29.560
Nothing going on at home.
Nothing at school.

123
00:04:29.644 --> 00:04:32.230
- And you believe her?
- There's some flags.

124
00:04:32.313 --> 00:04:34.482
Bruising in various stages
of healing.

125
00:04:34.524 --> 00:04:35.817
She's a little withdrawn.

126
00:04:35.858 --> 00:04:37.819
doesn't engage much
for girls her age.

127
00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:40.154
But she could just be
a little shy...

128
00:04:40.196 --> 00:04:41.781
or scared of being in here.

129
00:04:41.864 --> 00:04:43.866
- Or she's being abused.

130
00:04:43.908 --> 00:04:45.034
- That too.

131
00:04:45.118 --> 00:04:46.703
We'll find out more
when Dad shows up.

132
00:04:46.786 --> 00:04:48.830
- Yep.
If he shows up.

133
00:04:52.041 --> 00:04:54.085
- I need a hand here!

134
00:04:54.168 --> 00:04:57.547
[object snaps]
- There's the first barb out.

135
00:04:57.630 --> 00:04:59.340
All right. Javadi. you're up.

136
00:04:59.382 --> 00:05:02.010
[monitor beeping]

137
00:05:02.051 --> 00:05:03.845
Okay. so you're gonna
want to clamp

138
00:05:03.886 --> 00:05:06.389
where the shaft meets the barb.

139
00:05:06.431 --> 00:05:07.598
- Mm-hmm.
- Yep.

140
00:05:07.682 --> 00:05:09.559
Stabilize the skin.

141
00:05:09.642 --> 00:05:12.061
- Not so close
so as to stick yourself.

142
00:05:12.103 --> 00:05:13.479
I've seen that once or twice.

143
00:05:13.563 --> 00:05:15.898
- Uh. pull up at 90 degrees.

144
00:05:15.982 --> 00:05:17.692
- Harder.
Yep.

145
00:05:17.734 --> 00:05:19.027
Harder.

146
00:05:19.068 --> 00:05:20.028
- Oh.

147
00:05:20.069 --> 00:05:22.030
Do we suture those?

148
00:05:22.071 --> 00:05:23.698
- Nope. just a Band-Aid.

149
00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:26.200
- Mel. we need orders.
- Right.

150
00:05:26.242 --> 00:05:27.243
- I got a rainbow.

151
00:05:27.327 --> 00:05:29.912
- Uh. CBC...

152
00:05:29.954 --> 00:05:33.207
CMP. UA. blood alcohol.
and tox screen.

153
00:05:33.249 --> 00:05:34.584
- All of the above.

154
00:05:34.667 --> 00:05:35.918
- Cap. if this
young man's stable.

155
00:05:36.002 --> 00:05:37.378
can he go to Central 10 pronto?

156
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:38.588
Double trauma at the back door.

157
00:05:38.629 --> 00:05:40.673
- Okay. you heard the boss.
Let's get going.

158
00:05:40.757 --> 00:05:43.217
Today is starting to heat up.

159
00:05:43.259 --> 00:05:46.846
[indistinct chatter.
telephone ringing]

160
00:05:46.929 --> 00:05:49.766
- Mark Yee. 32-year-old
restrained driver.

161
00:05:49.807 --> 00:05:51.183
auto versus motorcycle.

162
00:05:51.267 --> 00:05:53.728
Altered with normal BP.
satting 99 on 2 liters.

163
00:05:53.770 --> 00:05:55.730
- We're at
the hospital now. Mark.

164
00:05:55.772 --> 00:05:57.482
What's wrong with him?
Why isn't he talking?

165
00:05:57.565 --> 00:05:59.317
- His wife. Nancy.
front-seat passenger.

166
00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:00.943
declined transport.
- I'm fine.

167
00:06:00.985 --> 00:06:04.155
We weren't going all that fast.
The motorcycle ran the light.

168
00:06:04.238 --> 00:06:06.282
- I'm Dr. Robby.
This is Dr. Al-Hashimi.

169
00:06:06.366 --> 00:06:07.784
- Nice to meet you.
- And this is Nurse Dana.

170
00:06:07.825 --> 00:06:08.993
She's our charge nurse.

171
00:06:09.077 --> 00:06:10.536
We need to look over
your husband.

172
00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:11.954
- Hello. Let's step over here
for a minute. hon.

173
00:06:11.996 --> 00:06:13.247
Let them get to work. okay?

174
00:06:13.289 --> 00:06:15.291
Antoine. Larry.
transfer out here.

175
00:06:15.375 --> 00:06:16.751
T-1 will be open in a sec.

176
00:06:16.793 --> 00:06:18.127
- Aye. aye. Cap.

177
00:06:18.169 --> 00:06:20.463
- One. two. three.

178
00:06:20.505 --> 00:06:22.215
[grunts]
- Incoming.

179
00:06:22.298 --> 00:06:23.925
- Okay. Joy. you stay with me.

180
00:06:23.966 --> 00:06:26.344
Samira. you stay
with Dr. Al-Hashimi.

181
00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:29.472
- Open skull fracture.

182
00:06:29.514 --> 00:06:31.099
Tubed him
for agonal respirations.

183
00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.808
BP 60 palp initially.

184
00:06:32.892 --> 00:06:35.269
Started a liter of NS.
but lost his pulse en route.

185
00:06:37.105 --> 00:06:39.148
- Oh. boy.
this doesn't look good.

186
00:06:39.190 --> 00:06:40.691
- One. two. three.

187
00:06:40.775 --> 00:06:42.568
[grunts]
Joy. check his pupils.

188
00:06:42.652 --> 00:06:44.028
Somebody hand me
a pair of scissors.

189
00:06:48.658 --> 00:06:50.159
- 8 millimeters.
Nonreactive.

190
00:06:50.243 --> 00:06:53.079
- AKA blown pupils.
fixed and dilated.

191
00:06:53.162 --> 00:06:54.455
Oh.
[groans]

192
00:06:54.497 --> 00:06:56.249
- Crushed skull with tons
of gray matter extravasation.

193
00:06:56.332 --> 00:06:57.792
At least it was quick.

194
00:06:57.834 --> 00:06:59.669
- No helmet?
- Nope. 'cause he took

195
00:06:59.710 --> 00:07:01.129
the PennDOT
Motorcycle Safety Course.

196
00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:02.505
- Isn't that
what you took. Robby?

197
00:07:02.588 --> 00:07:05.383
- Hold compressions.
Yes. but I still wear a helmet.

198
00:07:05.466 --> 00:07:07.510
Is he a donor?
- Also nope.

199
00:07:07.593 --> 00:07:08.845
- That is too bad.

200
00:07:08.886 --> 00:07:11.556
Asystole.
I think we are done here.

201
00:07:11.639 --> 00:07:13.349
- What's next door?
- The guy who hit him.

202
00:07:13.433 --> 00:07:14.809
Joy. you're with me.

203
00:07:14.851 --> 00:07:17.520
- What about a moment
of reflection? I thought--

204
00:07:17.562 --> 00:07:19.272
- He'll still be dead
when we get back.

205
00:07:19.355 --> 00:07:22.316
- Pulse ox 99.
BP 108 over 72.

206
00:07:22.358 --> 00:07:23.359
- EFAST negative.

207
00:07:23.443 --> 00:07:24.694
- Hell of a lot better
than the guy next door.

208
00:07:24.735 --> 00:07:26.028
- How's the airway?
- Good volume.

209
00:07:26.112 --> 00:07:28.364
Good sats.
Gag reflex...

210
00:07:28.448 --> 00:07:30.324
- [gags]
- Present.

211
00:07:30.366 --> 00:07:31.868
- Intubate?
- Maybe.

212
00:07:31.909 --> 00:07:33.034
Maybe not.
- Mr. Yee?

213
00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:34.871
Joy. sternal rub
on his chest. like this.

214
00:07:34.912 --> 00:07:36.038
Really hard. please.

215
00:07:36.122 --> 00:07:38.040
Mr. Yee?
- [groans]

216
00:07:38.124 --> 00:07:40.209
- Spontaneous eye movement.
Responds to pain.

217
00:07:40.293 --> 00:07:42.211
GCS is 10.
Borderline for intubation.

218
00:07:42.295 --> 00:07:45.131
- No muscle tone--flaccid
paralysis in the left arm.

219
00:07:45.214 --> 00:07:46.716
- Same on the right.
- And both legs.

220
00:07:46.757 --> 00:07:48.718
- Add towels to both sides of
the collar for more stability.

221
00:07:48.759 --> 00:07:50.887
Let's not make this worse.

222
00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:53.848
- Pan scan with 3D
reconstruction of the spine.

223
00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:55.308
- He's quadriplegic?

224
00:07:55.391 --> 00:07:57.727
- If so. it's
a low cervical injury.

225
00:07:57.768 --> 00:07:59.896
- Why is that. Joy?
- Uh...

226
00:07:59.937 --> 00:08:03.774
- C3. 4. and 5 helps you
breathe to stay alive.

227
00:08:03.858 --> 00:08:05.401
- Mr. Montrose...

228
00:08:05.443 --> 00:08:08.237
you can't just be wandering
around. talking to patients.

229
00:08:08.279 --> 00:08:10.072
- Well. that's--
that's what I do.

230
00:08:10.114 --> 00:08:11.616
I'm a greeter at Walmart.

231
00:08:11.699 --> 00:08:15.161
I get paid to wander
and to talk to folks.

232
00:08:15.244 --> 00:08:17.413
- Well. as a--
as a personal favor to me.

233
00:08:17.497 --> 00:08:20.582
can you at least stay
in your general vicinity?

234
00:08:20.625 --> 00:08:22.752
I can get you a wheelchair
while we wait for your X-rays.

235
00:08:22.835 --> 00:08:24.086
but it might take a minute.

236
00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:25.588
- [clears throat]
My dear. I cannot sit.

237
00:08:25.671 --> 00:08:27.673
My backside is killing me
from where I fell on it.

238
00:08:27.757 --> 00:08:30.259
which is an embarrassing
admission to make

239
00:08:30.301 --> 00:08:32.929
to such a lovely woman.
- [chuckles]

240
00:08:33.011 --> 00:08:34.554
Well. thank you
for the compliment.

241
00:08:34.597 --> 00:08:36.307
but there's no need
to be embarrassed.

242
00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:37.808
You took a very nasty fall.

243
00:08:37.892 --> 00:08:40.727
- Well. then may I say that
one look in your beautiful eyes

244
00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:42.938
and I think I'm falling again.

245
00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:46.234
[both laughing]

246
00:08:46.275 --> 00:08:47.652
- What a charmer.

247
00:08:47.735 --> 00:08:49.946
Just for that. I'm gonna
get you a foam donut.

248
00:08:49.987 --> 00:08:52.281
It's the eighth wonder
of the world.

249
00:08:52.365 --> 00:08:54.784
- Pretty great laugh
you got there. Doc.

250
00:08:54.867 --> 00:08:56.786
- [chuckles]

251
00:08:56.827 --> 00:08:59.121
Oh. God.
My witch's cackle?

252
00:08:59.205 --> 00:09:00.957
- Got CT results
for Mr. Williams.

253
00:09:00.998 --> 00:09:02.542
- Ah.

254
00:09:04.877 --> 00:09:06.963
Oh. wow.

255
00:09:08.881 --> 00:09:10.132
Okay.

256
00:09:10.216 --> 00:09:11.634
- Okay.

257
00:09:11.717 --> 00:09:13.886
- Ah.
Right on time.

258
00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:15.972
Just--just getting full.

259
00:09:16.013 --> 00:09:17.807
Yeah. I'm ready
for number five.

260
00:09:17.848 --> 00:09:19.642
- That's impressive.
- Uh-huh.

261
00:09:19.725 --> 00:09:21.894
- Yeah. there's more
where that came from.

262
00:09:21.978 --> 00:09:25.648
Although. uh. my intake
is running low.

263
00:09:25.731 --> 00:09:27.483
- Yeah. well. two more bottles
ought to do it.

264
00:09:27.525 --> 00:09:29.443
Then we'll drain your tooth.
and we'll get you out of here

265
00:09:29.485 --> 00:09:31.904
before the fireworks tonight.
- Oh.

266
00:09:31.988 --> 00:09:33.114
- Okay. Clamped.

267
00:09:33.155 --> 00:09:35.992
Ogilvie. make the change.

268
00:09:36.075 --> 00:09:38.869
- Okay.
- Mm-hmm.

269
00:09:38.953 --> 00:09:41.956
- All right.
Let her rip.

270
00:09:41.998 --> 00:09:44.458
- Flowing like a river.
- [chuckles]

271
00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:47.336
I love me some fireworks.

272
00:09:47.378 --> 00:09:49.338
- Oh. yeah?

273
00:09:49.422 --> 00:09:52.341
- Shit. I-I met Mr. Zambelli...

274
00:09:52.425 --> 00:09:54.135
- Lean forward.

275
00:09:54.176 --> 00:09:56.220
- Many times on the field.

276
00:09:56.304 --> 00:09:58.889
- Who's Mr. Zambelli?

277
00:09:58.973 --> 00:10:00.391
- Son. you don't know fireworks

278
00:10:00.474 --> 00:10:02.977
if you don't know
the name Zambelli.

279
00:10:03.019 --> 00:10:04.937
He helped Pittsburgh become

280
00:10:05.021 --> 00:10:07.523
the firework capital
of America.

281
00:10:07.607 --> 00:10:09.859
You did know that. didn't you?

282
00:10:09.942 --> 00:10:11.527
- No.
- Ah.

283
00:10:11.611 --> 00:10:14.864
Y'all don't know nothing
about pyrotechnics.

284
00:10:14.905 --> 00:10:16.324
Stick to doctoring.

285
00:10:16.365 --> 00:10:18.534
- Yes. will do.

286
00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:28.336
- [sighs] I'm sure you have
some questions.

287
00:10:28.377 --> 00:10:31.714
I know it's a lot to take in.

288
00:10:31.797 --> 00:10:34.175
- It's a tumor.

289
00:10:34.216 --> 00:10:35.343
It's a brain tumor.

290
00:10:35.384 --> 00:10:38.429
- Well. it's a mass.
about 4 centimeters.

291
00:10:38.512 --> 00:10:40.556
in the frontal lobe.

292
00:10:41.807 --> 00:10:43.768
- Is it cancer?

293
00:10:43.851 --> 00:10:46.270
- We can't say
for sure right now.

294
00:10:46.354 --> 00:10:47.730
It could be many things--

295
00:10:47.813 --> 00:10:50.900
uh. infection. inflammation.

296
00:10:50.983 --> 00:10:53.903
a benign cyst.

297
00:10:53.944 --> 00:10:57.198
- Is it what made me fall?

298
00:10:57.239 --> 00:10:59.116
- Yeah. possibly.

299
00:11:01.035 --> 00:11:03.746
We'd like to keep you here
and treat with dexamethasone.

300
00:11:03.829 --> 00:11:05.873
which is a steroid
to take down the swelling.

301
00:11:05.915 --> 00:11:07.375
- Hmm.
- And then we'll need

302
00:11:07.416 --> 00:11:10.336
a brain biopsy
to know exactly what it is.

303
00:11:10.419 --> 00:11:14.256
- What. you're--you're gonna
cut open my head?

304
00:11:14.298 --> 00:11:16.592
- It's just a small hole.

305
00:11:16.634 --> 00:11:20.429
We'll do a-a CT-guided
stereotactical biopsy

306
00:11:20.513 --> 00:11:22.765
with a-a blunt. thin needle...
- [sighs]

307
00:11:22.848 --> 00:11:25.601
- Which sounds crazy. but it's
actually pretty amazing.

308
00:11:25.685 --> 00:11:28.604
I mean. most patients
go home the next day.

309
00:11:32.441 --> 00:11:34.777
- I don't know.

310
00:11:34.819 --> 00:11:38.280
What do you think I should do?

311
00:11:38.364 --> 00:11:41.784
- I think this is
a pretty good plan.

312
00:11:41.826 --> 00:11:43.160
- Okay.
- Yeah?

313
00:11:43.244 --> 00:11:47.248
- BP 95 over 67.

314
00:11:47.289 --> 00:11:49.250
- Seems a little
on the low side.

315
00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:50.751
- It is.

316
00:11:50.793 --> 00:11:52.962
Have you ever had
low blood pressure in the past?

317
00:11:53.003 --> 00:11:55.965
- No. sir. My blood pressure's
always high.

318
00:11:56.006 --> 00:11:58.968
- Hold still. sir.
No talking while we do the EKG.

319
00:11:59.051 --> 00:12:01.637
- The Hansens all run high.
except for Monty.

320
00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:04.014
He ran low. but he's dead.
- That's not helpful.

321
00:12:04.098 --> 00:12:06.934
You want to help.
quit playing family pharmacist.

322
00:12:06.976 --> 00:12:09.395
- Pooling meds is how
we've always done it.

323
00:12:09.478 --> 00:12:10.730
You put everything
in a big pile

324
00:12:10.813 --> 00:12:11.981
in the middle of the table--

325
00:12:12.022 --> 00:12:13.315
- Well. look where
that got us now.

326
00:12:13.357 --> 00:12:15.443
- No. I'm gonna jump in here
and echo that sharing meds

327
00:12:15.484 --> 00:12:16.610
which haven't been
prescribed to you

328
00:12:16.652 --> 00:12:17.903
is actually a real big no-no.

329
00:12:17.987 --> 00:12:18.946
How we doing on remembering

330
00:12:18.988 --> 00:12:20.322
what your brother
might've taken?

331
00:12:20.406 --> 00:12:21.490
- We could call
back to the house.

332
00:12:21.574 --> 00:12:24.118
- Great idea.
Okay.

333
00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:26.495
Whatever little round pill
you took. sir.

334
00:12:26.537 --> 00:12:28.581
has caused your heart rate
and blood pressure

335
00:12:28.664 --> 00:12:30.833
to drop so low.
you're at risk of fainting.

336
00:12:30.875 --> 00:12:33.002
falling. or having
a serious injury.

337
00:12:33.043 --> 00:12:34.128
- Oh.

338
00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:35.755
- We need to take
him back to the ER

339
00:12:35.838 --> 00:12:36.839
so he can get
a liter of fluids.

340
00:12:36.881 --> 00:12:38.174
we can check his blood tests

341
00:12:38.215 --> 00:12:39.508
and monitor his heart rate
and blood pressure

342
00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:41.677
till he recovers.

343
00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:43.345
- Pulse ox holding steady
at 99.

344
00:12:43.387 --> 00:12:44.513
Good tidal volume.

345
00:12:44.555 --> 00:12:46.182
- How you doing there. Mr. Yee?

346
00:12:46.223 --> 00:12:47.516
- Scanner can take him now.

347
00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:48.851
- I'll check the results
from upstairs.

348
00:12:48.934 --> 00:12:51.645
- Why is he so altered?
- Could be concussion.

349
00:12:51.687 --> 00:12:53.522
Maybe a small
intracranial hemorrhage.

350
00:12:53.606 --> 00:12:56.066
- All will be revealed
by the Donut of Truth.

351
00:12:56.150 --> 00:12:58.736
- Need a portable monitor.
- Joy. stay with him. please.

352
00:12:58.819 --> 00:13:00.696
See if the radiologist
can give us a STAT read.

353
00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:01.822
- How is he?

354
00:13:01.864 --> 00:13:04.200
Did I hear someone
say he's paralyzed?

355
00:13:04.241 --> 00:13:06.535
- There are signs of weakness
in both arms and legs.

356
00:13:06.577 --> 00:13:08.871
But before we can make
any prognosis.

357
00:13:08.954 --> 00:13:10.206
we'll need a full-body scan.

358
00:13:10.289 --> 00:13:12.541
- Head CT will show us
any brain injury.

359
00:13:12.625 --> 00:13:14.710
Neck CT will show us
any spinal-cord injury.

360
00:13:14.794 --> 00:13:17.463
Chest. abdomen. pelvis will
rule out any internal bleeding.

361
00:13:17.546 --> 00:13:18.547
- Oh. my God.

362
00:13:18.589 --> 00:13:21.383
- The scans should only take
about 15 minutes.

363
00:13:21.467 --> 00:13:24.220
In the meantime. perhaps you'd
let us look you over as well?

364
00:13:24.261 --> 00:13:26.514
- I'm fine.
The medics checked me.

365
00:13:26.555 --> 00:13:29.058
I just want to stay
with my husband.

366
00:13:29.099 --> 00:13:31.310
- Well. you can't go
into the CT with him.

367
00:13:31.393 --> 00:13:33.562
but you can wait just outside
if you like.

368
00:13:33.604 --> 00:13:34.855
- Excuse me.
- Princess. this is Nancy.

369
00:13:34.897 --> 00:13:36.482
Mrs. Yee is gonna go
with her husband to CT.

370
00:13:36.565 --> 00:13:37.566
Will you show her where to go?

371
00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:40.319
- Sure. Come on in.
- Thank you.

372
00:13:42.112 --> 00:13:43.906
- So what's the plan now?

373
00:13:43.989 --> 00:13:46.075
Keep observing me
in my natural habitat?

374
00:13:46.158 --> 00:13:47.535
No telling
what I might do next.

375
00:13:47.576 --> 00:13:49.078
- I think I've got the gist.

376
00:13:49.161 --> 00:13:51.247
How about we each take a lap
and meet here

377
00:13:51.288 --> 00:13:52.748
when Mr. Yee is back from CT?

378
00:13:52.790 --> 00:13:54.625
- Splitting up so soon?

379
00:13:54.708 --> 00:13:57.795
- You're free to see
other people. Dr. Robinavitch.

380
00:13:57.878 --> 00:14:00.631
I'm looking for cooperation.
not commitment.

381
00:14:02.508 --> 00:14:05.135
- [chuckles]
[device whirs]

382
00:14:05.219 --> 00:14:07.221
- So you bandaged
the burn yourself?

383
00:14:07.263 --> 00:14:08.973
- Oh. no. no. no. no.
no. no. no. no--

384
00:14:09.056 --> 00:14:11.100
- Ma'am. you're--you're making
it difficult for me

385
00:14:11.141 --> 00:14:12.768
to see under this dressing.

386
00:14:12.852 --> 00:14:16.105
Is that a tablecloth?
- Part of a window curtain.

387
00:14:16.188 --> 00:14:17.523
Cleaner than tablecloth.

388
00:14:17.606 --> 00:14:19.233
I'll wait for the doctor.
Thank you.

389
00:14:19.275 --> 00:14:22.611
- May I ask how this happened?

390
00:14:22.695 --> 00:14:24.405
- For weeks on end.
the kids with their

391
00:14:24.446 --> 00:14:26.699
guchnyy firecrackers.
going all day and night.

392
00:14:26.782 --> 00:14:28.784
- Oh. i-is this
a firecracker burn?

393
00:14:28.826 --> 00:14:31.787
- No. sweetie.
this is from the full samovar

394
00:14:31.829 --> 00:14:34.707
I drop on the floor
when the sh--

395
00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:37.293
the firecrackers
started going on again.

396
00:14:37.376 --> 00:14:39.295
- I'm sorry.
What's a samovar?

397
00:14:39.336 --> 00:14:42.548
- It is a big metal urn
for coffee or tea.

398
00:14:42.631 --> 00:14:44.633
They can get super-duper hot.

399
00:14:44.717 --> 00:14:46.927
and I was never allowed
to touch ours.

400
00:14:46.969 --> 00:14:48.304
Uh. hello. Mrs. Kovalenko.

401
00:14:48.387 --> 00:14:49.638
My name is
Dr. Michael Robinavitch.

402
00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:51.307
Everybody calls me Dr. Robby.

403
00:14:51.348 --> 00:14:54.310
- Robinavitch? Jewish?
- You guessed it.

404
00:14:54.351 --> 00:14:57.813
And I see that you are
here today for a burn.

405
00:14:57.855 --> 00:14:59.189
Why don't we take a look?

406
00:14:59.273 --> 00:15:00.816
- Oh. not married?

407
00:15:00.858 --> 00:15:02.484
- No. I'm not married.

408
00:15:02.568 --> 00:15:05.154
- [chuckles]
Do you attend synagogue?

409
00:15:05.195 --> 00:15:08.115
- Uh. not for a while.

410
00:15:08.157 --> 00:15:12.036
I mean. High Holidays mostly.

411
00:15:12.119 --> 00:15:13.203
- Where?

412
00:15:13.287 --> 00:15:14.872
- Ooh.
- [whimpers]

413
00:15:14.955 --> 00:15:17.166
- What did you put on this?

414
00:15:17.249 --> 00:15:18.792
- Where?
- On your burn.

415
00:15:18.834 --> 00:15:21.003
Is this honey?
- Yes. honey.

416
00:15:21.086 --> 00:15:23.005
Where do you go on holy days?

417
00:15:23.088 --> 00:15:26.008
- Uh. my grandparents. um--

418
00:15:26.091 --> 00:15:27.760
I grew up
going to Rodef Shalom.

419
00:15:27.843 --> 00:15:28.761
You?

420
00:15:28.844 --> 00:15:31.138
- Tree of Life.

421
00:15:32.848 --> 00:15:34.266
- They're rebuilding.

422
00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:36.685
- Yes. something new.

423
00:15:36.727 --> 00:15:40.189
Remember. Rebuild. Renew.

424
00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.650
That's the slogan.

425
00:15:44.693 --> 00:15:47.363
- I'm sorry.
did you say "honey"?

426
00:15:47.446 --> 00:15:49.531
- You think honey's funny?

427
00:15:49.615 --> 00:15:51.533
Works like a charm.

428
00:15:51.617 --> 00:15:53.702
My father kept bees.
I know.

429
00:15:53.744 --> 00:15:56.997
- If the honey is medical grade
and the burns are not too bad.

430
00:15:57.039 --> 00:15:59.083
honey actually does have
some antibacterial

431
00:15:59.165 --> 00:16:00.709
and anti-inflammatory
properties.

432
00:16:00.751 --> 00:16:03.253
However. these burns
are very deep in some places.

433
00:16:03.337 --> 00:16:05.673
They're going
to need debridement.

434
00:16:05.714 --> 00:16:08.676
I'm glad you came in.

435
00:16:08.717 --> 00:16:10.511
- That's what I thought.

436
00:16:10.552 --> 00:16:14.515
I was hoping no.
but I figured as much.

437
00:16:14.556 --> 00:16:15.599
- Not to worry.

438
00:16:15.683 --> 00:16:18.477
We are gonna have you
patched up and home

439
00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:20.145
in time for dinner
and fireworks.

440
00:16:20.229 --> 00:16:22.064
- No.

441
00:16:22.106 --> 00:16:23.565
No more fireworks.

442
00:16:23.607 --> 00:16:24.817
No.

443
00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:25.901
- Okay.

444
00:16:25.985 --> 00:16:30.239
- Anyone here treating
Kylie Connors?

445
00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:31.740
- She's my daughter.

446
00:16:31.782 --> 00:16:33.826
She's nine.
I'm Benny Connors.

447
00:16:33.909 --> 00:16:36.245
- Mr. Connors. I'm Dr. Santos.

448
00:16:36.328 --> 00:16:37.663
I'm treating Kylie.

449
00:16:37.746 --> 00:16:39.248
- Is she okay?
Can I see her?

450
00:16:39.289 --> 00:16:41.208
My--my girlfriend. Gina.
says she got a cut on her chin?

451
00:16:41.250 --> 00:16:42.251
- Yeah. I can take you to her.

452
00:16:42.334 --> 00:16:44.044
She has a small
laceration on her chin.

453
00:16:44.086 --> 00:16:46.255
but it was easily repaired
with medical superglue.

454
00:16:46.338 --> 00:16:48.424
so no stitches necessary.
- Okay.

455
00:16:48.507 --> 00:16:50.968
- She chipped a tooth.
but it's a baby tooth.

456
00:16:51.051 --> 00:16:52.761
so it won't need dental work.

457
00:16:52.845 --> 00:16:54.722
- All right.
well. that's a relief.

458
00:16:54.763 --> 00:16:57.224
- Has Kylie had
any previous injuries?

459
00:16:57.266 --> 00:16:58.892
- Uh. yeah.

460
00:16:58.934 --> 00:17:01.103
She. um--she broke
her wrist last year.

461
00:17:01.186 --> 00:17:02.771
She was skateboarding.

462
00:17:02.813 --> 00:17:05.941
- Dana. if you could get Dylan
to come to North 1.

463
00:17:06.025 --> 00:17:08.068
and Ahmad.
- You bet.

464
00:17:08.109 --> 00:17:10.404
- Okay. I got it now.
One. two. three.

465
00:17:10.445 --> 00:17:11.613
- Daddy. you came.

466
00:17:11.696 --> 00:17:13.449
- Baby. what's going on. huh?

467
00:17:13.531 --> 00:17:15.159
- My tooth broke.
and my chin got cut.

468
00:17:15.242 --> 00:17:18.454
- Oh. no.
[smooches]

469
00:17:18.494 --> 00:17:19.621
What happened?

470
00:17:19.704 --> 00:17:21.915
- She was running
up the stairs.

471
00:17:21.957 --> 00:17:24.585
- Gina was chasing me.
- We were playing.

472
00:17:24.626 --> 00:17:27.128
- As I was saying. Mr. Connors.
the laceration is pretty minor.

473
00:17:27.171 --> 00:17:28.130
- On the stairs?

474
00:17:28.213 --> 00:17:30.299
- It was an accident.
- Perhaps we can--

475
00:17:30.382 --> 00:17:31.925
- An accident
that wouldn't have happened

476
00:17:31.967 --> 00:17:33.260
if you weren't running
up the stairs.

477
00:17:33.302 --> 00:17:34.428
Do you understand
what I'm saying?

478
00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:36.889
This is the last thing
that I need right now.

479
00:17:36.972 --> 00:17:38.599
is her mother finding out
that she got hurt

480
00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:40.225
when she's with you.
- It was an accident.

481
00:17:40.309 --> 00:17:41.769
And before you get
all high and mighty.

482
00:17:41.810 --> 00:17:43.729
I've got questions of my own.
- Like what?

483
00:17:43.812 --> 00:17:45.064
- Hey. Mr. Connors.

484
00:17:45.147 --> 00:17:46.940
I'm sorry. I meant to be here
when you arrived.

485
00:17:46.982 --> 00:17:48.901
I'm Dylan Easton.
I'm with Social Services.

486
00:17:48.984 --> 00:17:50.069
- We have insurance.
Thank you.

487
00:17:50.152 --> 00:17:51.695
- Perhaps we can step outside
and chat for a second?

488
00:17:51.779 --> 00:17:53.655
I can fill you in
on where we are.

489
00:17:53.697 --> 00:17:55.491
Hey. uh. Jesse. do you want
to keep Kylie entertained

490
00:17:55.574 --> 00:17:57.159
for a few minutes while I...
- Absolutely.

491
00:17:57.242 --> 00:17:58.202
- Borrow her dad?

492
00:17:58.285 --> 00:17:59.369
We'll just head down
to the family room.

493
00:17:59.453 --> 00:18:01.622
It's a little quieter there.

494
00:18:01.663 --> 00:18:03.373
- Why do I got to talk
to a social worker?

495
00:18:03.457 --> 00:18:05.876
- Anytime a child is injured.
we have some standard questions

496
00:18:05.959 --> 00:18:07.377
that we ask parents
and caregivers.

497
00:18:07.461 --> 00:18:10.547
- Good. That's fine. Great.
Ask me here.

498
00:18:10.631 --> 00:18:14.134
- Well. we noticed
some bruising on Kylie's body.

499
00:18:14.176 --> 00:18:17.513
some old. some new.
on her back and legs.

500
00:18:17.596 --> 00:18:19.723
Any idea how she got those?
- Yeah. soccer.

501
00:18:19.807 --> 00:18:20.974
She plays for a club team.

502
00:18:21.016 --> 00:18:22.226
They're. you know.
little girls.

503
00:18:22.309 --> 00:18:24.353
but they play like they're
in "The Hunger Games."

504
00:18:24.394 --> 00:18:26.438
- Well. I understand
that you and Kylie do

505
00:18:26.522 --> 00:18:29.358
a fair amount of roughhousing.

506
00:18:29.399 --> 00:18:31.360
- What?

507
00:18:31.401 --> 00:18:34.029
I'm sorry.
Are you fucking kidding me?

508
00:18:34.113 --> 00:18:35.197
Where are you going with this?

509
00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:36.532
Are you saying
that I hurt my daughter?

510
00:18:36.573 --> 00:18:37.825
- Mr. Connors.
nobody's saying that--

511
00:18:37.866 --> 00:18:38.951
- Oh. no. no. no.
no. no. no. no. no.

512
00:18:39.034 --> 00:18:40.160
Gina!
- Mr. Connors--

513
00:18:40.202 --> 00:18:41.537
- Just--just--Gina!

514
00:18:41.578 --> 00:18:42.538
- Sir. take a breath.

515
00:18:42.579 --> 00:18:43.705
- Gina. what did you say
to them?

516
00:18:43.747 --> 00:18:45.541
- Nothing.
I said that you're a great dad.

517
00:18:45.582 --> 00:18:47.042
- Okay. What else?

518
00:18:47.084 --> 00:18:48.544
- That you guys
like to wrestle.

519
00:18:48.585 --> 00:18:49.711
- Jesus Christ.
- What?

520
00:18:49.795 --> 00:18:51.213
They wanted to know where
all her bruises are from.

521
00:18:51.296 --> 00:18:53.132
- Who the fuck are you to talk
about me and my daughter?

522
00:18:53.215 --> 00:18:54.675
- Who the fuck am I?
- Yeah. that's what I'm asking.

523
00:18:54.716 --> 00:18:55.843
- Who the fuck am I?

524
00:18:55.884 --> 00:18:57.219
- Hey. big man. take
one more fucking step--

525
00:18:57.261 --> 00:18:59.596
- Hey. that's enough.
You need to calm down.

526
00:18:59.680 --> 00:19:01.598
- Hey. everybody.
back the fuck up!

527
00:19:01.682 --> 00:19:03.016
- Stop! Stop! Stop! Stop!

528
00:19:03.058 --> 00:19:06.061
Kylie's platelets
are only 9.000.

529
00:19:06.145 --> 00:19:08.063
- What does that mean?
- [sighs]

530
00:19:08.147 --> 00:19:10.941
It's--it's not what we thought.

531
00:19:11.024 --> 00:19:13.277
It's probably ITP.

532
00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:15.612
- What the hell is ITP?

533
00:19:15.696 --> 00:19:17.948
- Something we can treat.

534
00:19:24.121 --> 00:19:26.707
- You feel that?
- Mm. no.

535
00:19:26.748 --> 00:19:28.375
- Excellent.

536
00:19:28.417 --> 00:19:30.252
This is looking very good.

537
00:19:30.335 --> 00:19:32.337
- Ah. Tell Mr. Kovalenko.

538
00:19:32.421 --> 00:19:35.924
[laughter]

539
00:19:36.008 --> 00:19:37.259
- Mrs. Kovalenko?

540
00:19:37.301 --> 00:19:39.178
- Yes?
Yana. please.

541
00:19:39.261 --> 00:19:43.098
- Yana. you mentioned
that you dropped the samovar

542
00:19:43.182 --> 00:19:46.602
when you heard firecrackers.

543
00:19:46.643 --> 00:19:47.686
- Yeah.

544
00:19:50.689 --> 00:19:54.443
I was on my way inside--

545
00:19:54.484 --> 00:19:57.571
October 27. 2018--

546
00:19:57.613 --> 00:20:00.532
to the synagogue
when the shooting started.

547
00:20:05.245 --> 00:20:08.123
There was nothing I could do.

548
00:20:08.207 --> 00:20:09.791
I went in...

549
00:20:09.833 --> 00:20:12.294
after the police arrived.

550
00:20:12.377 --> 00:20:14.463
I felt I had to.

551
00:20:16.298 --> 00:20:18.467
I'm better now.

552
00:20:18.550 --> 00:20:20.969
But...

553
00:20:21.011 --> 00:20:24.306
[voice breaking]
New Year's Eve. Fourth of July.

554
00:20:24.389 --> 00:20:27.809
when--when kids have
their fireworks

555
00:20:27.893 --> 00:20:30.687
and firecrackers. I--

556
00:20:32.856 --> 00:20:35.734
- There is no clock
on how long it takes.

557
00:20:35.817 --> 00:20:37.277
- [scoffs]

558
00:20:37.319 --> 00:20:38.987
No clock.

559
00:20:39.029 --> 00:20:41.823
You must be joking.

560
00:20:41.907 --> 00:20:43.951
[knock at door]

561
00:20:43.992 --> 00:20:45.244
- Robby?
- Yep.

562
00:20:45.327 --> 00:20:47.454
- Mark Yee is back from CT.
- Oh. okay.

563
00:20:47.496 --> 00:20:48.956
Um. Perlah. why don't we go
ahead and see if we can put

564
00:20:48.997 --> 00:20:50.749
a nonstick dressing on this?

565
00:20:50.832 --> 00:20:53.001
And I will come back.
and we can discuss

566
00:20:53.085 --> 00:20:54.461
aftercare instructions.

567
00:20:54.503 --> 00:20:55.963
- Yeah. you got it. boss.

568
00:20:56.004 --> 00:20:58.090
- Thank you. Doctor.

569
00:21:05.013 --> 00:21:07.474
[door closes]

570
00:21:07.516 --> 00:21:10.227
[indistinct chatter]

571
00:21:10.310 --> 00:21:12.813
- Vitals stable.
Pulse ox holding at 99.

572
00:21:12.854 --> 00:21:14.856
- Okay.
Heart and lungs look good.

573
00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:17.025
[cell phone rings]

574
00:21:17.067 --> 00:21:19.361
- Dr. Mohan.
- Dr. Robby?

575
00:21:19.403 --> 00:21:22.656
- Yeah?
[sighs]

576
00:21:22.698 --> 00:21:25.200
- Please make him be okay.

577
00:21:25.284 --> 00:21:27.160
- I can assure you that we
are gonna do absolutely--

578
00:21:27.202 --> 00:21:29.830
- Everything you can.
I know.

579
00:21:29.871 --> 00:21:31.373
God. this is all my fault.

580
00:21:31.456 --> 00:21:34.334
- Mrs. Yee--
- Oh. he's been so stressed.

581
00:21:34.376 --> 00:21:36.712
So I planned this weekend away
at Seven Springs.

582
00:21:36.753 --> 00:21:39.298
but he didn't want to go
because of work.

583
00:21:39.381 --> 00:21:42.384
So we fought
this whole morning.

584
00:21:42.467 --> 00:21:44.886
And then I...

585
00:21:44.928 --> 00:21:48.181
I said awful things.

586
00:21:48.223 --> 00:21:50.183
Those can't be the last words
we say to each other.

587
00:21:50.225 --> 00:21:51.810
Doctor. please.

588
00:21:51.893 --> 00:21:54.730
- Good news.
CT looks normal.

589
00:21:54.813 --> 00:21:56.481
No bleeding inside the skull.

590
00:21:56.565 --> 00:21:59.318
C-spine. no fractures seen.

591
00:21:59.401 --> 00:22:01.737
- He didn't break his neck?
- Then why is he paralyzed?

592
00:22:01.778 --> 00:22:03.363
- You can have spinal injuries

593
00:22:03.405 --> 00:22:05.115
without
radiologic abnormalities.

594
00:22:05.198 --> 00:22:08.035
- Sometimes it doesn't show up
on CT. only on MRI.

595
00:22:08.076 --> 00:22:10.454
[cell phone rings]
- Dr. Mohan.

596
00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:14.416
Are you sure?

597
00:22:17.419 --> 00:22:19.212
Okay.

598
00:22:19.254 --> 00:22:21.256
Critical potassium level. 1.2.

599
00:22:21.340 --> 00:22:22.883
- Wow.

600
00:22:22.924 --> 00:22:24.468
- Okay.
- That's crazy low.

601
00:22:24.551 --> 00:22:26.553
- Uh. extremely low potassium
with generalized weakness

602
00:22:26.595 --> 00:22:28.430
and no cervical injury.

603
00:22:28.513 --> 00:22:29.765
We may be looking at--

604
00:22:29.848 --> 00:22:31.600
- Hypokalemic
periodic paralysis.

605
00:22:31.683 --> 00:22:32.768
- What is that?

606
00:22:32.809 --> 00:22:34.353
- It's a rare condition
where potassium gets shifted

607
00:22:34.436 --> 00:22:36.521
into the cells.
causing profound weakness.

608
00:22:36.605 --> 00:22:37.731
just like paralysis.

609
00:22:37.773 --> 00:22:39.441
- Will he get better?
- Yes.

610
00:22:39.483 --> 00:22:41.109
Back to normal in a few hours.

611
00:22:41.193 --> 00:22:42.444
- In a f--

612
00:22:42.527 --> 00:22:44.196
- Replete slowly.
10 MEQ of KCl--

613
00:22:44.279 --> 00:22:47.240
- [crying]
Thank you so much.

614
00:22:47.282 --> 00:22:48.784
Did you hear that. Mark?

615
00:22:48.825 --> 00:22:52.537
Oh. baby.
you're gonna get better.

616
00:22:52.621 --> 00:22:54.790
Oh. baby.

617
00:22:54.831 --> 00:22:56.625
- All right. DD.
Hey. come on now. man.

618
00:22:56.666 --> 00:22:58.543
- Oh. how you doing. Duante?

619
00:22:58.627 --> 00:23:00.128
- Fine.
- Great.

620
00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:01.546
If you're fine. you go home.

621
00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:02.631
- Really?
- Yeah.

622
00:23:02.672 --> 00:23:05.759
- Mm-mm.
Hey. tell them.

623
00:23:05.801 --> 00:23:08.303
- Me and my sister
were making bracelets.

624
00:23:08.387 --> 00:23:12.307
and I put beads up my nose.

625
00:23:12.391 --> 00:23:13.809
- How many?

626
00:23:13.892 --> 00:23:15.268
- One on each side.

627
00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:17.938
- I got to ask--
why'd you stick them up there?

628
00:23:17.979 --> 00:23:19.648
See how many will fit?

629
00:23:19.689 --> 00:23:21.525
- To shoot them out
like rockets.

630
00:23:21.608 --> 00:23:22.651
- Mm.

631
00:23:22.692 --> 00:23:23.985
- But I breathed in.

632
00:23:24.069 --> 00:23:26.988
and they went deeper
and now won't come out.

633
00:23:27.072 --> 00:23:28.824
- Did you try anything at home?

634
00:23:28.907 --> 00:23:30.492
- Yeah. I tried blowing
in his mouth.

635
00:23:30.575 --> 00:23:32.202
but just got a little snot
on my cheek.

636
00:23:32.285 --> 00:23:33.370
- "A" for effort. Dad.

637
00:23:33.453 --> 00:23:36.123
Okay. we need to take a look
with a little flashlight.

638
00:23:36.164 --> 00:23:37.999
Okay?
- Okay.

639
00:23:38.041 --> 00:23:39.501
- This is what I have
to look forward to?

640
00:23:39.584 --> 00:23:41.837
- This and so much more.

641
00:23:41.878 --> 00:23:44.464
Red bead below
the inferior turbinate.

642
00:23:44.506 --> 00:23:46.925
- I...

643
00:23:47.008 --> 00:23:48.343
got a blue one.

644
00:23:48.385 --> 00:23:50.971
Afrin. benzocaine.
Katz extractor?

645
00:23:51.012 --> 00:23:53.098
- Yep. Dad. looks like we got
to go up and get them.

646
00:23:53.181 --> 00:23:55.809
- No way he's sitting still.
- Oh. he'll be numbed up.

647
00:23:55.851 --> 00:23:57.018
- You don't know this child.

648
00:23:57.060 --> 00:24:00.021
- Hey. Duante.
you like video games?

649
00:24:00.063 --> 00:24:01.857
- Everybody does.

650
00:24:01.940 --> 00:24:04.151
- We have a 3D video game.

651
00:24:04.192 --> 00:24:06.069
- Yeah.
- Cool.

652
00:24:06.153 --> 00:24:07.279
- [chuckles]

653
00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:13.535
- That's KCl and saline
at 10 MEQ per hour.

654
00:24:13.618 --> 00:24:15.704
- We avoid dextrose
because the insulin response

655
00:24:15.745 --> 00:24:17.038
drops the K even more.

656
00:24:17.122 --> 00:24:19.875
- If it's genetic. why didn't
it happen when he was a kid?

657
00:24:19.958 --> 00:24:22.252
- It usually starts
after the teen years.

658
00:24:22.335 --> 00:24:23.378
- And it can be intermittent.

659
00:24:23.462 --> 00:24:26.506
Sometimes it's triggered
by intense exercise or stress.

660
00:24:26.548 --> 00:24:28.508
- We've been married
eight years.

661
00:24:28.550 --> 00:24:30.677
We've had fights.
He's never collapsed.

662
00:24:30.719 --> 00:24:32.179
- If his thyroid
gets overactive.

663
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:34.014
that brings it on
later in life.

664
00:24:34.055 --> 00:24:36.558
- I ordered TSH. T3. T4.

665
00:24:36.641 --> 00:24:38.894
- So now we just wait?

666
00:24:38.977 --> 00:24:41.146
[monitors beeping rapidly]

667
00:24:41.229 --> 00:24:42.522
- Bag him.
Starting compressions.

668
00:24:42.564 --> 00:24:45.150
Charge to 200.
- What is happening?

669
00:24:45.233 --> 00:24:47.152
- Low potassium
can harm electrical activity

670
00:24:47.235 --> 00:24:48.737
in the heart.
- Charged.

671
00:24:48.778 --> 00:24:50.739
- Clear.
- Clear.

672
00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:52.616
- Resuming compressions.

673
00:24:54.117 --> 00:24:57.996
- So your little girl was ITP?
- Go figure.

674
00:24:58.079 --> 00:25:00.540
Nothing like a zebra
to kick-start your morning.

675
00:25:00.582 --> 00:25:03.168
- Well. it's better
than the alternative.

676
00:25:03.251 --> 00:25:04.753
- True.

677
00:25:04.794 --> 00:25:06.922
- ITP.

678
00:25:07.005 --> 00:25:09.424
So that's. uh. intra--

679
00:25:09.508 --> 00:25:11.092
- Immune thrombocytopenia.

680
00:25:11.176 --> 00:25:14.596
- Used to be called idiopathic
thrombocytopenic purpura.

681
00:25:14.679 --> 00:25:16.431
Know what "idiopathic" means?

682
00:25:16.515 --> 00:25:18.558
- That we don't know
the exact cause.

683
00:25:18.600 --> 00:25:20.435
- It means the patient
is pathetic

684
00:25:20.477 --> 00:25:22.938
and the doctor is an idiot.

685
00:25:24.481 --> 00:25:26.274
- Just checked
on baby Jane Doe.

686
00:25:26.358 --> 00:25:28.985
Looking good.
Taking formula well.

687
00:25:29.069 --> 00:25:30.820
- We're here
to take a statement.

688
00:25:30.904 --> 00:25:33.615
We're looking
for a Tony Chinchiolo.

689
00:25:33.698 --> 00:25:37.244
- Yo!
Right over here. boys!

690
00:25:37.285 --> 00:25:39.204
Well. officers.

691
00:25:39.287 --> 00:25:41.581
- Heard you had some trouble
over at the campus library.

692
00:25:41.623 --> 00:25:43.917
- Shit.
Let me just say--

693
00:25:43.959 --> 00:25:46.545
new appreciation
for what you guys do every day.

694
00:25:46.628 --> 00:25:49.047
Frickin' junkie jungle. right?

695
00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:51.216
- At the campus library?

696
00:25:51.299 --> 00:25:52.467
- Yeah.

697
00:25:52.509 --> 00:25:53.760
- Thumb and forefinger
make a C.

698
00:25:53.802 --> 00:25:55.470
Bottom three fingers make an E
for jaw lift.

699
00:25:55.512 --> 00:25:57.472
One breath every five seconds.
Come here. try it.

700
00:25:57.556 --> 00:25:59.391
- About two minutes
since defibrillation.

701
00:25:59.474 --> 00:26:02.477
- Holding compressions.
- Normal sinus.

702
00:26:02.561 --> 00:26:04.646
- Carotid. Strong carotid.
Okay. let's try for BP.

703
00:26:04.729 --> 00:26:06.314
- Why don't we check
after the shock?

704
00:26:06.356 --> 00:26:08.233
- 2024 ACLS guidelines.

705
00:26:08.316 --> 00:26:10.235
Patients can remain pulseless
for a little bit.

706
00:26:10.318 --> 00:26:11.695
even after successful defib.

707
00:26:11.778 --> 00:26:14.197
- He came back with one shock.
That's as good as it gets.

708
00:26:14.281 --> 00:26:16.658
- 104 over 68.
- Good squeeze. Good EF.

709
00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:18.660
- Spontaneous respirations.
Okay. let's lift him up.

710
00:26:18.743 --> 00:26:21.037
- He's breathing on his own--
excellent sign.

711
00:26:21.121 --> 00:26:22.372
- Oh. God.

712
00:26:22.455 --> 00:26:25.834
Can I touch him?
- Of course.

713
00:26:25.917 --> 00:26:27.210
- Oh. Mark.

714
00:26:27.294 --> 00:26:30.297
Hey.
- [groans softly]

715
00:26:30.338 --> 00:26:32.048
- Oh. shit.

716
00:26:32.132 --> 00:26:33.383
We need a gurney!

717
00:26:33.466 --> 00:26:35.218
Nancy?

718
00:26:35.302 --> 00:26:37.220
Mrs. Yee?

719
00:26:37.304 --> 00:26:38.513
Mrs. Yee?

720
00:26:38.555 --> 00:26:40.015
Weak carotid.
Shallow breaths.

721
00:26:40.056 --> 00:26:41.850
- Did she vasovagal
from stress?

722
00:26:41.891 --> 00:26:43.018
- Can't assume that.

723
00:26:43.059 --> 00:26:44.853
Positive seat belt si--
oh. shit.

724
00:26:44.894 --> 00:26:46.521
Hang two units of O-neg
on the rapid infuser.

725
00:26:46.605 --> 00:26:48.148
Somebody call Garcia.
Shit.

726
00:26:48.189 --> 00:26:49.983
We really should have insisted
on examining her.

727
00:26:50.025 --> 00:26:51.318
- Okay. I got the head.

728
00:26:51.359 --> 00:26:53.612
- Platelets are these
tiny things in the blood

729
00:26:53.695 --> 00:26:55.196
that help it clot.

730
00:26:55.238 --> 00:26:58.617
And thrombocytopenia is fancy
for "low platelets."

731
00:26:58.700 --> 00:27:01.036
which explains why your skin
bruises so easily.

732
00:27:01.119 --> 00:27:02.329
- And what causes it?

733
00:27:02.370 --> 00:27:04.372
- It's actually
her immune system

734
00:27:04.456 --> 00:27:06.458
that's causing
the destruction of platelets.

735
00:27:06.541 --> 00:27:08.460
Sometimes
it's a triggered response

736
00:27:08.543 --> 00:27:11.796
to. uh. an environmental factor
or virus.

737
00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:14.716
- And what's the treatment?
What are you giving her?

738
00:27:14.799 --> 00:27:17.344
- We'll be treating her
with high-dose steroids

739
00:27:17.385 --> 00:27:20.221
to suppress the immune system
and IV immunoglobulin.

740
00:27:20.305 --> 00:27:23.058
which reduces the destruction
of the platelets in the spleen.

741
00:27:23.099 --> 00:27:24.351
- Can I go home?

742
00:27:24.392 --> 00:27:26.353
- You're gonna have to stay
in the hospital

743
00:27:26.394 --> 00:27:28.021
for about three days

744
00:27:28.063 --> 00:27:30.357
to make sure
that the treatment is working.

745
00:27:30.398 --> 00:27:32.067
- Okay. Okay.

746
00:27:32.108 --> 00:27:34.069
So when can she get
a room in the hospital?

747
00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:35.737
- That is
an excellent question.

748
00:27:35.779 --> 00:27:37.280
I'm going to see
if I can make that happen

749
00:27:37.364 --> 00:27:38.406
sooner rather than later.

750
00:27:38.490 --> 00:27:40.367
but it might take a while.
- Okay.

751
00:27:40.408 --> 00:27:42.369
- GPS says I should be there
by 11:00.

752
00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:45.163
- Do you have any other
questions for me. ma'am?

753
00:27:45.246 --> 00:27:47.916
- No. I'm sure I will.
but I'll let you go for now.

754
00:27:47.999 --> 00:27:49.250
Thank you. Benny.

755
00:27:49.334 --> 00:27:50.502
- All right.
I'll see you when you get here.

756
00:27:50.585 --> 00:27:52.170
- See you soon. baby.
I love you.

757
00:27:52.253 --> 00:27:55.090
- Bye. Mom.
Love you too.

758
00:27:56.424 --> 00:27:58.176
- There you are.

759
00:27:58.259 --> 00:27:59.511
- And there you are.

760
00:27:59.594 --> 00:28:02.430
- Don't try to charm me.
You promised to stay put.

761
00:28:02.514 --> 00:28:04.182
- I was going
to come right back.

762
00:28:04.265 --> 00:28:06.017
My backside is killing me.

763
00:28:06.101 --> 00:28:09.270
I need to keep moving.
or I get all achy and stiff.

764
00:28:09.312 --> 00:28:12.357
- Well. I got you
this foam donut to sit on

765
00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:15.235
while we wait for your X-rays.
- Hmm.

766
00:28:15.276 --> 00:28:17.737
Dr. Hazel Eyes. it says here

767
00:28:17.779 --> 00:28:22.617
that it's only supposed to take
an hour or two for an X-ray.

768
00:28:22.701 --> 00:28:25.578
- Well. the patient passport
holiday edition

769
00:28:25.620 --> 00:28:27.288
would better reflect reality.

770
00:28:27.330 --> 00:28:29.582
It could be double that.

771
00:28:29.624 --> 00:28:31.334
- There's no need for reality.

772
00:28:31.418 --> 00:28:33.628
We romantics...

773
00:28:33.712 --> 00:28:37.132
prefer la reve. the dream.

774
00:28:37.215 --> 00:28:38.800
- We do. do we?

775
00:28:38.842 --> 00:28:40.844
- Oui.

776
00:28:40.927 --> 00:28:44.139
♪ La mer
qu'on voit danser ♪

777
00:28:44.222 --> 00:28:46.975
♪ Le long des golfes clairs ♪

778
00:28:47.016 --> 00:28:49.144
♪ A des reflets
d'argent. la mer ♪

779
00:28:49.227 --> 00:28:50.603
- [laughs]
Right.

780
00:28:50.645 --> 00:28:54.149
- ♪ Des reflets
changeants sous la pluie ♪

781
00:28:54.190 --> 00:28:56.401
- Hey. save a dance for me.

782
00:28:56.484 --> 00:28:58.987
- Uh. yeah. okay. I will.

783
00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:00.405
- Dr. McKay?
- Yes.

784
00:29:00.488 --> 00:29:01.656
This is Gretchen Williams.

785
00:29:01.698 --> 00:29:03.491
- Actually. it's Lambdin.
- Ah.

786
00:29:03.575 --> 00:29:05.744
- You called about my
ex-husband. Michael Williams.

787
00:29:05.827 --> 00:29:07.829
- Yeah. Yes. yes.
Thank you for coming in.

788
00:29:07.912 --> 00:29:10.165
You were. um. listed
as his emergency contact.

789
00:29:10.206 --> 00:29:11.499
- Yeah. I don't know why.

790
00:29:11.583 --> 00:29:14.294
We have been divorced
for years.

791
00:29:14.335 --> 00:29:15.628
Is he all right?

792
00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:18.798
- He's--he's going
through a lot right now.

793
00:29:18.840 --> 00:29:20.550
Would you like to see him?

794
00:29:22.510 --> 00:29:23.678
- Uh. okay.

795
00:29:23.762 --> 00:29:27.474
Leo. can you zoom in and please
hold it a little steadier?

796
00:29:27.515 --> 00:29:29.100
- Okay.

797
00:29:31.311 --> 00:29:32.687
- Okay.

798
00:29:32.729 --> 00:29:34.314
Atorvastatin.

799
00:29:34.355 --> 00:29:35.899
Simvastatin.

800
00:29:35.982 --> 00:29:37.192
Ezetimibe.

801
00:29:37.275 --> 00:29:39.736
Those are all
high-cholesterol medications.

802
00:29:39.819 --> 00:29:41.488
Can you go to the right?

803
00:29:41.529 --> 00:29:43.740
Lisinopril.

804
00:29:43.823 --> 00:29:45.742
Losartan. Propranolol.

805
00:29:45.825 --> 00:29:47.744
- Wait. wait. that's it.

806
00:29:47.827 --> 00:29:49.287
Wendy's pile.

807
00:29:49.370 --> 00:29:50.497
Yellowish bottle.

808
00:29:50.538 --> 00:29:52.624
little. round blue pills.
just like I said.

809
00:29:52.707 --> 00:29:54.667
- Propranolol?
- Bingo. little lady.

810
00:29:54.709 --> 00:29:57.128
- Okay. yeah. well. this makes
a lot of sense now.

811
00:29:57.212 --> 00:30:01.132
Um. propranolol is a
high-blood-pressure medication.

812
00:30:01.216 --> 00:30:04.010
Those are 20 milligrams each.

813
00:30:04.052 --> 00:30:06.179
and the starting dose
is 40 mgs.

814
00:30:06.221 --> 00:30:07.972
How many pills did you take?

815
00:30:08.056 --> 00:30:10.850
- No. ma'am. I-I went
just before I came here.

816
00:30:10.892 --> 00:30:12.560
- Dad.

817
00:30:12.602 --> 00:30:15.313
- Um--pill--how many pills
did you take?

818
00:30:15.396 --> 00:30:20.068
- Oh. uh.
I think four. maybe five.

819
00:30:20.151 --> 00:30:21.903
- That is a lot.
Okay.

820
00:30:21.986 --> 00:30:24.197
- Full stomach. mind you.

821
00:30:24.239 --> 00:30:27.408
- Well. um. the good news is.
it has a short half-life.

822
00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:30.036
so. um. we're gonna need
to keep you

823
00:30:30.078 --> 00:30:31.704
for about four hours
to monitor.

824
00:30:31.746 --> 00:30:33.915
But then you'll be able
to rejoin

825
00:30:33.998 --> 00:30:35.917
for all the late-afternoon
festivities.

826
00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.419
- All right.
- Whoo!

827
00:30:38.461 --> 00:30:40.129
[monitor beeping rapidly]
- Unit 3 and 4 running in.

828
00:30:40.213 --> 00:30:42.048
BP 84 over 56.
Heart rate 112.

829
00:30:42.090 --> 00:30:43.800
- Free fluid's
much bigger than before.

830
00:30:43.883 --> 00:30:45.885
- She's not turning the corner.
OR is holding a room.

831
00:30:45.927 --> 00:30:47.428
- I'll let the husband know.

832
00:30:47.512 --> 00:30:48.763
- Why did you guys wait
so long to check her?

833
00:30:48.847 --> 00:30:50.598
- Good vitals in the field.
No distress.

834
00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:51.933
She refused to sign in.

835
00:30:51.975 --> 00:30:53.268
- You should have
convinced her.

836
00:30:53.351 --> 00:30:54.686
- 20/20 hindsight.
She was stable.

837
00:30:54.769 --> 00:30:55.770
- Until she wasn't.

838
00:30:55.812 --> 00:30:57.564
- Next time. I'll use
my X-ray vision goggles.

839
00:30:57.605 --> 00:30:59.566
- Let's get her upstairs.

840
00:30:59.607 --> 00:31:02.277
- Got to do an accu-check
on my DKA patient.

841
00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:04.112
Thanks for the backup.

842
00:31:04.195 --> 00:31:05.989
- Anytime.

843
00:31:09.492 --> 00:31:12.203
- Now. try and lift
your arm. Mark.

844
00:31:14.163 --> 00:31:16.082
- I'm trying.
Can't do it.

845
00:31:16.124 --> 00:31:20.587
- But you are getting stronger.
and your speech is improving.

846
00:31:20.628 --> 00:31:22.922
- How did I lose
so much potassium?

847
00:31:22.964 --> 00:31:26.175
- You didn't lose it.
It got shifted into cells.

848
00:31:26.259 --> 00:31:28.469
When it comes back.
you'll return to normal.

849
00:31:28.511 --> 00:31:29.679
- Where's Nancy?

850
00:31:29.762 --> 00:31:31.764
- She had an injury to her
spleen right about here

851
00:31:31.806 --> 00:31:33.641
with some internal bleeding.

852
00:31:33.683 --> 00:31:34.976
- Oh. God.

853
00:31:35.059 --> 00:31:36.352
- She passed out
from blood loss.

854
00:31:36.436 --> 00:31:38.646
We were able to transfuse her.
and she's now on her way

855
00:31:38.688 --> 00:31:40.815
to surgery
to repair that damage.

856
00:31:40.899 --> 00:31:43.026
- This is my fault.

857
00:31:43.109 --> 00:31:46.696
She was trying to--
[sighs]

858
00:31:46.779 --> 00:31:51.159
She booked a trip
for us. for me.

859
00:31:51.242 --> 00:31:54.120
I fought her the whole time.
I've been--

860
00:31:54.162 --> 00:31:57.165
[sighs]

861
00:31:57.206 --> 00:31:59.000
Please don't--

862
00:31:59.042 --> 00:32:01.920
oh. my God.
please don't let her die.

863
00:32:02.003 --> 00:32:03.338
Please.

864
00:32:03.379 --> 00:32:06.132
- I can assure you
that she is in excellent hands.

865
00:32:08.176 --> 00:32:09.844
- Is this how it works?

866
00:32:09.886 --> 00:32:12.305
- How what works?

867
00:32:12.347 --> 00:32:14.849
- You think things
are important...

868
00:32:14.891 --> 00:32:18.353
that everything's so important.

869
00:32:18.394 --> 00:32:20.563
And then you end up here
and see.

870
00:32:23.608 --> 00:32:26.861
- Yeah. that is how it works.

871
00:32:26.945 --> 00:32:29.822
- No. it's a small hole.

872
00:32:29.864 --> 00:32:32.325
Like the size of a dime.
right. Doc?

873
00:32:32.367 --> 00:32:34.744
- Mm-hmm.
Yeah. even smaller.

874
00:32:34.827 --> 00:32:36.829
It's a minor enough procedure

875
00:32:36.871 --> 00:32:39.374
that most patients go home
the next day.

876
00:32:39.457 --> 00:32:40.500
- And then?

877
00:32:40.541 --> 00:32:42.669
- And then they'll know
what it is

878
00:32:42.710 --> 00:32:43.878
and how to treat it.

879
00:32:43.962 --> 00:32:47.090
Isn't that right?
- Yeah. exactly.

880
00:32:49.050 --> 00:32:51.928
- I'm sorry
that they called you.

881
00:32:52.011 --> 00:32:53.930
I never updated the form.
I guess.

882
00:32:54.013 --> 00:32:56.140
- No. no. it's okay.
I'm--

883
00:32:57.725 --> 00:33:01.479
You know. they called. and I
was just kind of surprised.

884
00:33:01.562 --> 00:33:03.564
[both chuckle]

885
00:33:03.606 --> 00:33:05.358
- Well. you didn't have
to come.

886
00:33:07.068 --> 00:33:08.277
- But I did.

887
00:33:11.781 --> 00:33:14.033
- I heard you got married.

888
00:33:14.075 --> 00:33:15.702
Congratulations.

889
00:33:15.743 --> 00:33:17.495
- Thank you.

890
00:33:19.414 --> 00:33:22.125
- I hope he treats you well.

891
00:33:23.918 --> 00:33:26.004
You deserve to be happy.

892
00:33:29.173 --> 00:33:31.259
- [sighs]

893
00:33:31.300 --> 00:33:35.430
I'm really sorry you're going
through this. Michael.

894
00:33:35.513 --> 00:33:37.640
- Yeah.

895
00:33:37.724 --> 00:33:40.601
Me too.

896
00:33:40.643 --> 00:33:43.688
But you know me--
I'm a survivor.

897
00:33:48.026 --> 00:33:52.488
- Why don't I-I leave you guys
to talk for a few minutes?

898
00:33:52.572 --> 00:33:55.158
I have a patient to check on.

899
00:33:56.534 --> 00:33:58.536
- Sure.
- Yeah.

900
00:34:00.038 --> 00:34:02.457
- Mr. Diaz should be improving
after 2 liters.

901
00:34:02.498 --> 00:34:03.875
Blood sugar?

902
00:34:03.958 --> 00:34:05.877
- Down from 521 to 436.

903
00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:07.211
- That's good. right?

904
00:34:07.295 --> 00:34:08.629
- Moving
in the right direction.

905
00:34:08.670 --> 00:34:10.797
Were you able to get ahold
of your mom?

906
00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:13.051
- Yes. She's on her way.
She doesn't have a car.

907
00:34:13.134 --> 00:34:15.469
She takes buses.
so it takes longer.

908
00:34:15.553 --> 00:34:18.306
I'm sorry.
- Don't be.

909
00:34:18.389 --> 00:34:21.934
Current insulin is 0.1 units
per kilo per hour.

910
00:34:21.976 --> 00:34:22.976
Next steps?

911
00:34:23.018 --> 00:34:24.645
- Once the glucose
is down to 250.

912
00:34:24.687 --> 00:34:27.315
reduce the insulin to
0.05 units per kilo per hour.

913
00:34:27.356 --> 00:34:28.940
- Because you can normalize
the blood sugar

914
00:34:28.983 --> 00:34:31.360
before you clear the ketones.
and you don't get hypoglycemia.

915
00:34:31.444 --> 00:34:34.155
- But as treatment continues.
you'll have to give IV dextrose

916
00:34:34.197 --> 00:34:36.616
to keep the blood glucose
in between 150 and 200

917
00:34:36.657 --> 00:34:37.867
while the insulin drip
clears the ketones.

918
00:34:37.949 --> 00:34:39.659
- Obviously.

919
00:34:39.744 --> 00:34:41.496
- I'm sorry. what?

920
00:34:43.206 --> 00:34:44.456
- Got it.

921
00:34:44.498 --> 00:34:46.333
- Duante. what are you doing
in there. son?

922
00:34:46.417 --> 00:34:47.835
- I'm a rabbit.

923
00:34:47.877 --> 00:34:50.129
grabbing all the carrots
before the farmer gets me.

924
00:34:50.170 --> 00:34:51.714
- Keep going.

925
00:34:51.797 --> 00:34:55.342
This is a Katz extractor
with a tiny balloon at the end.

926
00:34:55.426 --> 00:34:57.470
What we're gonna do is. we're
gonna slip it past the bead.

927
00:34:57.512 --> 00:34:59.055
inflate the balloon.
try to pull out the bead.

928
00:34:59.138 --> 00:35:01.307
- Is it painful?
- No. he's--he's numbed up.

929
00:35:01.349 --> 00:35:02.850
- Made it to level three.

930
00:35:02.892 --> 00:35:04.185
- And pretty distracted.

931
00:35:04.268 --> 00:35:06.479
- Dad's gonna hold
your head still. okay?

932
00:35:06.521 --> 00:35:09.023
- Look up.
- Okay.

933
00:35:09.107 --> 00:35:12.944
Now go back. perpendicular.

934
00:35:13.027 --> 00:35:15.113
below the turbinates.

935
00:35:16.447 --> 00:35:18.950
You guys ever hear
of John O'Donohue?

936
00:35:19.033 --> 00:35:20.201
- Mm-mm.
- No.

937
00:35:20.243 --> 00:35:21.619
- I've been reading him
a lot lately.

938
00:35:21.702 --> 00:35:25.039
He's got this book
of. um. blessings.

939
00:35:25.081 --> 00:35:27.333
And there's this one
about fatherhood.

940
00:35:27.375 --> 00:35:30.044
Really stuck with me.
[bead clatters]

941
00:35:30.086 --> 00:35:32.421
Voilà.
One red bead.

942
00:35:32.505 --> 00:35:34.882
- Yeah?
How's it go?

943
00:35:34.924 --> 00:35:38.719
- The ending goes.
"May you be gentle and loving.

944
00:35:38.803 --> 00:35:40.680
"clear and sure.

945
00:35:40.721 --> 00:35:43.558
"May you trust
in the unseen Providence

946
00:35:43.599 --> 00:35:45.893
"that has chosen you
to be a family.

947
00:35:45.935 --> 00:35:49.939
"May you stand sure
on your ground and know

948
00:35:50.022 --> 00:35:53.234
"that every grace you need
will unfold before you

949
00:35:53.317 --> 00:35:55.736
like all the mornings
of your life."

950
00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:57.864
- Hmm. That's good.

951
00:35:57.905 --> 00:36:02.827
- I'd add. support your woman
and pack good snacks.

952
00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:04.412
- That's beautiful.

953
00:36:04.453 --> 00:36:07.373
And it turns out. there's
no handbook for fatherhood.

954
00:36:07.415 --> 00:36:11.377
So I will take
all the wisdom I can.

955
00:36:11.419 --> 00:36:14.380
[bead clatters]
Blue bead out.

956
00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:20.761
- Anything else?

957
00:36:20.803 --> 00:36:23.389
- You tell me.
I have my own report to do.

958
00:36:23.431 --> 00:36:24.432
Anything I left out?

959
00:36:24.515 --> 00:36:25.850
- Labs are back on that kid.

960
00:36:25.933 --> 00:36:27.393
- We'll follow up
with Mr. Davis.

961
00:36:27.435 --> 00:36:30.313
- Yeah. when Mr. Davis
comes off the ceiling.

962
00:36:33.316 --> 00:36:35.401
- Jackson Davis...

963
00:36:35.443 --> 00:36:37.737
tox screen negative
for cocaine.

964
00:36:37.778 --> 00:36:42.158
amphetamines. marijuana.
PCP. benzos. and opioids.

965
00:36:42.241 --> 00:36:44.452
- So no drugs in his system?
- Nope.

966
00:36:44.535 --> 00:36:46.787
- Taser barbs on the back
of the victim's neck?

967
00:36:46.829 --> 00:36:48.289
- Yep.

968
00:36:51.125 --> 00:36:53.169
- Changes things. Tony.

969
00:36:53.252 --> 00:36:54.795
- Hey. Louie.
- [groans]

970
00:36:54.879 --> 00:36:57.632
- How we doing?
- Not so good.

971
00:36:57.673 --> 00:36:59.967
I could really use a drink.

972
00:37:00.009 --> 00:37:02.637
I f-feel a-a little empty.

973
00:37:02.678 --> 00:37:04.180
- Okay. well. empty
is what we want.

974
00:37:04.263 --> 00:37:06.307
And it looks like we are there.

975
00:37:06.349 --> 00:37:09.727
- Hey. well. if I can't get
a drink. my tooth.

976
00:37:09.810 --> 00:37:11.229
You--you got to do something.

977
00:37:11.312 --> 00:37:12.438
- We're gonna get
right to that.

978
00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:16.150
Let's hang some IV antibiotics.
3 grams of Unasyn.

979
00:37:16.234 --> 00:37:18.236
- Excellent.

980
00:37:18.319 --> 00:37:19.487
- He's gonna be right back.

981
00:37:19.528 --> 00:37:20.905
We're gonna numb it up
and drain it.

982
00:37:20.988 --> 00:37:22.740
Ten minutes. tops. okay?
- Oh.

983
00:37:22.823 --> 00:37:25.326
- Hey. uh. you said
you met Mr. Zambelli.

984
00:37:25.368 --> 00:37:27.411
the fireworks guy.
on the field.

985
00:37:27.495 --> 00:37:28.454
What field was that?

986
00:37:28.496 --> 00:37:32.124
- Uh. n-no more talking.
You got to fix my tooth.

987
00:37:32.166 --> 00:37:33.793
- Yeah. deal.

988
00:37:33.834 --> 00:37:35.503
- [grunts]

989
00:37:39.924 --> 00:37:42.510
- You're Muslim?

990
00:37:42.593 --> 00:37:45.137
- I am.

991
00:37:45.179 --> 00:37:46.639
- Thank you.

992
00:37:46.681 --> 00:37:48.599
- Oh. for what?

993
00:37:49.892 --> 00:37:52.228
- After the shooting.
it was the Muslims

994
00:37:52.311 --> 00:37:55.731
that came together for us
in support and...

995
00:37:55.815 --> 00:37:57.525
walked with us.

996
00:37:57.608 --> 00:37:59.193
You raised money.

997
00:37:59.235 --> 00:38:00.903
You...

998
00:38:00.987 --> 00:38:03.823
paid for all the funerals.

999
00:38:03.864 --> 00:38:06.367
Anyway...

1000
00:38:06.450 --> 00:38:07.868
thank you.
[door opens]

1001
00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:10.997
- Hello.
How's it going in here?

1002
00:38:11.038 --> 00:38:12.873
Did I miss all the gross stuff?

1003
00:38:12.915 --> 00:38:14.875
- Timed it perfectly.
- Excellent.

1004
00:38:14.959 --> 00:38:17.211
My job is all about delegation
and time management.

1005
00:38:17.295 --> 00:38:19.547
- Oh. not for much longer.
- That is very true.

1006
00:38:19.588 --> 00:38:21.132
- W-why for not longer?

1007
00:38:21.215 --> 00:38:24.135
- Because tomorrow I am leaving
to go on sabbatical.

1008
00:38:24.218 --> 00:38:27.388
- He's leaving us for
three months on a motorcycle.

1009
00:38:27.430 --> 00:38:29.974
- Motorcycle?
You're joking.

1010
00:38:30.057 --> 00:38:32.727
Why would you do this?
- Why? Why?

1011
00:38:32.768 --> 00:38:34.895
Why? Because--
- You're middle-aged man.

1012
00:38:34.979 --> 00:38:36.647
Don't be stupid.

1013
00:38:36.731 --> 00:38:38.607
- Don't hold back.
Tell me how you really feel.

1014
00:38:38.691 --> 00:38:41.235
- Forgive me for being blunt.
Dr. Robinavitch.

1015
00:38:41.277 --> 00:38:43.863
but how old are you. huh--50?

1016
00:38:43.904 --> 00:38:45.906
- Ish.
- Ish.

1017
00:38:45.948 --> 00:38:49.910
50-ish-year-old man
on a motorcycle--

1018
00:38:49.952 --> 00:38:50.911
very sad.

1019
00:38:50.953 --> 00:38:52.580
[laughter]

1020
00:38:52.663 --> 00:38:55.708
[indistinct chatter]

1021
00:39:02.089 --> 00:39:03.841
- I. um...

1022
00:39:05.634 --> 00:39:07.887
I-I-I don't know what to say.

1023
00:39:07.928 --> 00:39:10.181
Have you ever heard of ITP?

1024
00:39:10.264 --> 00:39:11.265
I never did.

1025
00:39:13.434 --> 00:39:15.603
I really appreciate you
bringing her here. okay?

1026
00:39:15.644 --> 00:39:17.897
- Of course.
What do you think I am?

1027
00:39:17.938 --> 00:39:19.231
Oh. that's right.

1028
00:39:19.273 --> 00:39:20.858
You think I'm some kind
of child abuser.

1029
00:39:20.941 --> 00:39:22.526
- No. I never said that--
- The fuck you didn't.

1030
00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:24.612
In front of all those people.
you made it sound like

1031
00:39:24.653 --> 00:39:25.780
she might have
been getting hurt

1032
00:39:25.821 --> 00:39:28.032
while I was watching her.
like it was my fault.

1033
00:39:28.115 --> 00:39:29.283
- You basically said
the same thing about me.

1034
00:39:29.367 --> 00:39:30.951
- No. I said that
you guys roughhouse--

1035
00:39:31.035 --> 00:39:32.620
that's all--because you do.

1036
00:39:32.661 --> 00:39:34.789
- You know I would never hurt
my daughter.

1037
00:39:34.872 --> 00:39:36.916
- Actually. I don't.

1038
00:39:36.957 --> 00:39:39.794
I've known you six months.
You could be anybody.

1039
00:39:39.877 --> 00:39:41.921
- Okay. well. I am sorry
for what I said. okay?

1040
00:39:41.962 --> 00:39:43.631
I was upset.
and I-I was worried.

1041
00:39:43.672 --> 00:39:45.132
And I just--
I said something stupid.

1042
00:39:45.216 --> 00:39:46.467
And I just--
- You think?

1043
00:39:46.550 --> 00:39:47.760
- Will you just fucking
let me finish?

1044
00:39:47.802 --> 00:39:49.845
- You are finished!

1045
00:39:49.929 --> 00:39:51.055
We're finished.

1046
00:39:53.224 --> 00:39:54.850
- Well. happy fucking
Fourth of July.

1047
00:39:54.934 --> 00:39:56.227
- Yeah. happy Independence Day.

1048
00:39:58.396 --> 00:40:01.273
[indistinct chatter]

1049
00:40:01.315 --> 00:40:03.984
- Excuse me?
[grunts]

1050
00:40:04.068 --> 00:40:05.986
- Yes?
What can I do for you?

1051
00:40:06.028 --> 00:40:08.155
- Uh. my wife and I
were in an accident.

1052
00:40:08.239 --> 00:40:11.534
Um. she's in surgery right now.

1053
00:40:11.617 --> 00:40:13.494
Would you mind holding
my phone up for me

1054
00:40:13.577 --> 00:40:15.996
so I could record
a message for her?

1055
00:40:16.038 --> 00:40:17.665
- Of course I will.

1056
00:40:17.706 --> 00:40:18.666
Happy to.

1057
00:40:18.707 --> 00:40:21.419
Oh. good. I have the same one.

1058
00:40:21.502 --> 00:40:23.254
I know how this works.

1059
00:40:25.214 --> 00:40:27.466
Okay.

1060
00:40:27.508 --> 00:40:28.634
Ready?

1061
00:40:28.676 --> 00:40:30.970
Go.
- [clears throat]

1062
00:40:31.011 --> 00:40:32.138
[sighs]

1063
00:40:32.179 --> 00:40:34.306
Hi. my love.

1064
00:40:34.348 --> 00:40:37.143
[clears throat]
So. uh...

1065
00:40:37.184 --> 00:40:41.105
I was listening
to this couple argue. uh...

1066
00:40:41.188 --> 00:40:42.982
and they were yelling.

1067
00:40:43.023 --> 00:40:45.568
Both so angry.

1068
00:40:47.486 --> 00:40:52.074
And I just wanted you
to know. um...

1069
00:40:52.158 --> 00:40:54.076
that I was wrong.

1070
00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:58.998
I was so wrong. and--
and I'm sorry about all of it.

1071
00:40:59.039 --> 00:41:00.499
Uh...

1072
00:41:02.209 --> 00:41:03.711
- Hey.

1073
00:41:03.752 --> 00:41:05.671
How you doing?
- [sighs]

1074
00:41:05.713 --> 00:41:07.715
I haven't seen him
in. like. four years.

1075
00:41:07.756 --> 00:41:10.551
- Oh.
I can't imagine.

1076
00:41:10.593 --> 00:41:12.720
That must have been--
- So crazy.

1077
00:41:12.761 --> 00:41:14.972
You know. things were not good
at the end.

1078
00:41:15.055 --> 00:41:17.558
He was
a really different person.

1079
00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:21.979
Huge temper. not like
when we first got married.

1080
00:41:22.062 --> 00:41:23.981
- I'm so sorry.

1081
00:41:25.274 --> 00:41:27.234
- Could that mass
have been there for a while

1082
00:41:27.318 --> 00:41:30.404
and only recently got worse?

1083
00:41:30.446 --> 00:41:31.697
- Yes.

1084
00:41:31.739 --> 00:41:34.492
- Could it be responsible
for how much he changed?

1085
00:41:34.575 --> 00:41:36.744
You know. his--
his moods and tempers?

1086
00:41:36.785 --> 00:41:40.915
He was--he was getting
into fights with strangers.

1087
00:41:40.998 --> 00:41:43.501
- It's possible.
[sighs]

1088
00:41:50.090 --> 00:41:51.550
- Oh.

1089
00:41:53.886 --> 00:41:55.679
Thank you.

1090
00:41:57.848 --> 00:42:01.894
Um. unless he's asked you
to change it.

1091
00:42:01.936 --> 00:42:05.231
would you please leave me as...

1092
00:42:05.272 --> 00:42:06.815
the emergency contact?

1093
00:42:06.899 --> 00:42:08.901
- Yeah. absolutely.

1094
00:42:14.073 --> 00:42:17.284
[door opens]

1095
00:42:17.368 --> 00:42:20.037
[sighs]

1096
00:42:20.120 --> 00:42:22.581
- Okay. I'm sending
Mrs. Kovalenko home

1097
00:42:22.623 --> 00:42:23.791
with burn dressing

1098
00:42:23.832 --> 00:42:25.876
but not before
she turned my sabbatical

1099
00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:28.587
into a midlife crisis.
- No comment.

1100
00:42:28.629 --> 00:42:30.589
- Wound check. two days.
- Got it.

1101
00:42:30.631 --> 00:42:32.132
- What about Kylie.
this little girl?

1102
00:42:32.216 --> 00:42:34.093
She gone up yet?
- Hopefully soon.

1103
00:42:34.134 --> 00:42:36.303
- Hey. we're starting to clear
some space around here.

1104
00:42:36.345 --> 00:42:38.389
- Yep.
[telephone ringing]

1105
00:42:38.472 --> 00:42:42.017
PTMC Charge Nurse.
Go ahead. Medic Command.

1106
00:42:43.561 --> 00:42:45.229
Is this a drill?

1107
00:42:45.312 --> 00:42:46.397
Is this a joke?

1108
00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:47.815
It's the Fourth
of fucking July.

1109
00:42:52.820 --> 00:42:54.530
Got it. Thanks.

1110
00:42:54.613 --> 00:42:56.365
- What's up?
- Westbridge has a Code Black

1111
00:42:56.448 --> 00:42:58.325
and is closing
to internal disaster.

1112
00:42:58.367 --> 00:43:00.327
Central's diverting all
their ambulance traffic to us.

1113
00:43:00.411 --> 00:43:02.496
- What's the issue?
- Comspec didn't say.

1114
00:43:02.538 --> 00:43:03.539
- Shit. it could be anything

1115
00:43:03.622 --> 00:43:05.165
from a flooding toilet
to a power outage.

1116
00:43:05.207 --> 00:43:06.792
How long?
- Didn't know.

1117
00:43:06.834 --> 00:43:09.128
- A couple of doctors
probably got the holiday flu.

1118
00:43:09.169 --> 00:43:11.046
and they're understaffed.

1119
00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:12.673
- [chuckles]

1120
00:43:12.715 --> 00:43:15.968
How come? How long?
How many?

1121
00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:18.012
Mm. mm. mm.

1122
00:43:18.095 --> 00:43:21.348
Sounds like
a betting grid to me.

1123
00:43:21.432 --> 00:43:23.434
We are back.

1124
00:43:24.852 --> 00:43:28.105
- Oh. I should have left
last night.
